04602nam a22007215i 9781400832774DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20092007nju    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979579140  a97814008327747 a10.1515/97814008327742doi  a(DE-B1597)479979  a(OCoLC)963845230  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aGV1785.F8bG37 2009eb 7aPER0030402bisacsh04a792.80280922221 aGarelick, Rhonda K., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aElectric Salome :bLoie Fuller's Performance of Modernism /cRhonda K. Garelick. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2009] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b44 halftones. 2 line illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One The Evolution of Fuller’s Performance Aesthetic -- tChapter Two Electric Salome: Loie Fuller at the World’s Fair of 1900 -- tChapter Three Fuller and the Romantic Ballet -- tChapter Four Scarring the Air: Loie Fuller’s Bodily Moderism -- tChapter Five Of Veils and Onion Skins: Fuller and Modern European Drama -- tAfterword Thoughts on Contemporary Traces of Fuller -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLoie Fuller was the most famous American in Europe throughout the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries. Rising from a small-time vaudeville career in the States, she attained international celebrity as a dancer, inventor, impresario, and one of the first women filmmakers in the world. Fuller befriended royalty and inspired artists such as Mallarmé, Toulouse-Lautrec, Rodin, Sarah Bernhardt, and Isadora Duncan. Today, though, she is remembered mainly as an untutored "pioneer" of modern dance and stage technology, the "electricity fairy" who created a sensation onstage whirling under colored spotlights. But in Rhonda Garelick's Electric Salome, Fuller finally receives her due as a major artist whose work helped lay a foundation for all modernist performance to come. The book demonstrates that Fuller was not a mere entertainer or precursor, but an artist of great psychological, emotional, and sexual expressiveness whose work illuminates the centrality of dance to modernism. Electric Salome places Fuller in the context of classical and modern ballet, Art Nouveau, Orientalism, surrealism, the birth of cinema, American modern dance, and European drama. It offers detailed close readings of texts and performances, situated within broader historical, cultural, and theoretical frameworks. Accessibly written, the book also recounts the human story of how an obscure, uneducated woman from the dustbowl of the American Midwest moved to Paris, became a star, and lived openly for decades as a lesbian.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDancersxUnited States. 0aDancerszUnited States. 0aModern dancexUnited States. 0aModern dance. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Dance / Modern.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140083277440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400832774423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400832774.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK